value.0: "Look who is back! If it isn't the hero of the hour! Strange as it might seem, I was just thinking, 'I wonder when that old hero friend of mine will come back to see me?' and *poof* in you walk."
"And how may I be of assistance today?"
"Were you able to free Stiletto?"
"Well, you are a bungler, aren't you. I'll keep selling you items, but don't expect anything else from me now."
"I am impressed, <FirstName>... very impressed."

value.0: "I guess that means that this package is for you. It had a little note that said, 'Please give this to my rescuer. S.' I figured you were the one, but I wanted to make sure."
"Then welcome to the thieves guild, <Lord/Lady> <FirstName>. You will now have access to a cheaper rate on our wares, and some special equipment as well."
"I can sense the power of this cloak. It is a rare and valuable gift, <FirstName>."
"Welcome to my humble shop, <Lord/Lady> <FirstName>. How might I be of assistance?"
"Well, well, well, if it isn't a customer, come to visit my humble shop." You look down to see a strange, slick halfling giving you a wide grin.
"Pleased to make your acquaintance, I am. The name is Sebastion Fitch, but my friends just call me Southpaw. I'm the thieves guildmaster, and you must be the new hero in town."
"There has been talk all over town about you and the election. So how can old Southpaw be of assistance today? Would you like to purchase some legitimate goods?"
"Very well, have a good day, <sir/madam>."
"Certainly! Just let me dig through some of this... lesser merchandise, so I can find you the good stuff."
"I have been told that you are a follower of Veragok, so I will give you a discounted price."
"Now, as a member of the guild, would you be wanting my regular merchandise, or something special?"
"One of my thieves raided an old wizard's tower not long ago and came back with some magical boots, bracers and a belt."
"All of these items are defensive in nature. The boots are worth about 5500 gold, but I would gladly sell it to you for 4500. Are you interested?"
<StartCheck>[Failure]</Start> "Sorry, but I have to pay the thief and the government, so I need some profit. 4500 is a good price for these beauties."
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> "Fine. For you, I'll drop it to 3500. That's the best I can do."
"There you go. I hope they help you."
"There you go. I hope they help you."
"I'm sorry. I forgot that I already sold the boots. Old age must be getting to me already."
"All of these items are defensive in nature. The bracers are worth about 8500 gold, but I would gladly sell it to you for 7500. Are you interested?"
<StartCheck>[Failure]</Start> "No, I really can't. I've had an offer on them already, but the guy hasn't shown up to pay for them yet."
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> "Fine. For you, I'll drop it to 6500. That's the best I can do."
"There you go. I hope they help you."
"There you go. I hope they help you."
"I'm sorry. I forgot that I already sold the bracers. Old age must be getting to me already."
"All of these items are defensive in nature. The belt is worth about 4500 gold, but I would gladly sell it to you for 4000. Are you interested?"
"Very well, if you find the funds I'll sell them to you later, so long as no one else buys them first."
<StartCheck>[Failure]</Start> "No, I really can't. I've had an offer on it already, but the guy hasn't shown up to pay for it yet."
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> "Fine. For you, I'll drop it to 3500. That's the best I can do."
"There you go. I hope it helps you."
"There you go. I hope it helps you."
"I'm sorry. I forgot that I already sold the belt. Old age must be getting to me already."
"Very well. Only the best prices for you."
"Information takes time and time is money, so let's make it quick, right?"
"Excellent! I am sure you must now be in a mood to purchase some of our fine, legitimate goods."
"The keep is a large place and there are those who know it better than I, and who have more time on their hands. I suggest you ask someone in the market place."
"Any other questions?"
"The guild has guidelines for our members to follow, to keep friction between the thieves and the local citizens to a minimum. We discourage assassins and we pay our taxes."
"But we don't like to give away guild secrets, so that is enough on that topic. Anything else?"
"As a member of our guild, you are welcome to purchase special goods from my hidden stock."
"When I was young I was caught cutting a purse from a noble. To teach me a lesson, the noble removed my hand with his sword."
"I have learned to be quite adept with my left hand. A Southpaw is a left-handed person, which I guess I am now, by default. I could have had a healer try to grow it back, but I'm used to it now."
"It serves as a reminder to me of why I try to help thieves stay alive. It also serves as a lesson to scare some of the young ones into staying straight."
"Killing can be an effective lesson, but only to those who do not die. You can't teach much to a corpse."
"Not really. Truth is, it is important for our survival in the keep."
"There is nothing noble about it. It is common sense."

"You can tell pretty quickly which young ones will make good thieves and which will just bungle the job and get caught. A job gone wrong can lead to deaths, something I encourage my thieves to avoid."
"Our thieves guild has guidelines that help to keep us welcome in the keep. Many of my best thieves are folk that no one would suspect at all."
"But that is really enough revelation of trade secrets, I think. Do you have other questions?"
"I have never met such a practical criminal. Your parents must be proud!"
"My father was a thief and my mother was a barmaid, so if they were still alive, I imagine they would indeed be proud. Can you say the same?"
"My father was a druid and my mother was a nymph. My father would like what I have become, but my mother would have been disgusted by my scars. I am too ugly for a nymph."
"You have nothing to be ashamed of girl. You seem to have more in your head than any nymph I've ever heard of. But we have wandered off topic."
"I no longer feel like speaking to you, <sir/madam>. Please make a purchase or leave my store."

"Enivid is a paladin and has a real dislike for what she calls 'shady' characters. She has tried to have the entire guild and my shop closed down before, but the Banner understood the politics better."
"Without me, the thieves would get out of control and then people start getting killed and merchandise gets shipped south, instead of remaining in the area."
"As it is, the government takes a tax from our coffers, helping to pay for the guards. But Enivid thinks she can just shut us down and hunt down the thieves."
"Of course, <sir/madam>. I am sorry to have gone off so. It is an emotional subject to me."
"I'm not sure if you actually grasp the realities of our situation any better than the Hand does. If Enivid only realized how much crime we prevent, she'd have to put us on the payroll."
"Then we could never support you. I am sorry. Are you interested in my goods, or will you be leaving now?"
Southpaw stares into your eyes, then nods and quickly pulls out a sheet of paper and a stylus. "You won't mind signing a document to that effect then, would you?"
<StartCheck>[Failure]</Start> "Very good, now I shall... wait a second... this isn't even your name! You don't think I have thieves who try these tricks all the time? Sign it for real!"
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> "Good enough. I shall keep this on hand, in case you try to break your word when all that power goes to your head."
"I guess the guild shall be voting for you as the next <Lord/Lady> of the Keep."
"What else can old Southpaw do for you?"
<StartCheck>[Failure]</Start> "Do I really look that gullible to you? Now sign it or walk."
<StartCheck>[Success]</Start> "It goes against my very nature, but I suppose I shall trust you."
"Half of being the <Lord/Lady> of the Keep is signing important papers. I guess we can safely assume you won't make much of a <Lord/Lady>."
"Therefore we could never support you. I am sorry. Are you interested in my goods, or will you be leaving now?"
[The document says that as the Lord of the Keep, you promise to uphold the current contract between the keep and the Guild.]
"It simply gives the guild a chance to defend any members in a court of law, and we get a vote among the guild masters. There are a few small legal points, but that's the essence."
"Perfect. I think we shall get along just fine, <Lord/Lady> <FirstName>. Now, is there anything else I can do for you?"
"We have specific rules regarding what our thieves are allowed to do. We do not allow assassinations, nor do we steal from the poor. That's more than you can say for most Thieves Guilds."
"There are other ways we help, but I think you get the picture. So? What do you think?"
"As a paladin, I would think your position would be as problematic as the current Hand's position is."

"I have a 'friend' who has gotten on the bad side of Enivid and languishes in prison at this very minute, crammed in there with the Masked Man's soldiers captured in the battle. If you freed him, I would vote for you."
"Either convince Enivid to set him free, or break him out of prison. Just be careful not to run around killing the guards. That would be bad form indeed."
"If that is what it takes, then yes. But if you can convince Enivid to release him, that would be all for the better."
"All he needs is his door opened, or get Enivid to order his release. Either way, once he is free return here."
"You don't sound terribly convinced you can do this. Try not to get Stiletto, the prisoner, killed."
"You mean besides the lands and wealth that come with the title <Lord/Lady> of the Keep? Perhaps Stiletto will have something for you, if you treat him well."
"Good. Try not to get Stiletto, the prisoner, killed. May Veragok cover you with his divine darkness and obscure you from your enemies."
"As a thief, I imagine you would be an excellent supporter of our cause."
"Would you be interested in joining our guild? Not only would we be willing to support your bid for the throne, but I can also offer you some 'special' purchases."
"Of course, <sir/madam>, we cannot all be rational, intelligent creatures, now can we? What can I do for you now?"
"A sadly common attitude within our guild. Still, we need the fresh blood."
"Good, we always need fresh blood. "
"Do you swear to obey our rules and respect the guild? Do you promise to protect our interests, should you win the election?"
"Protect your fellow thieves when you can. Use as little force as possible when taking a target (we don't like assassins... if they are detected)."
"Finally, sell your goods here. You can use other shopkeepers, but you support your guild by dealing with me. I will also protect your identity from the guards, which others might not. Do you swear?"

value.0: "Then welcome to the thieves guild, <Lord/Lady> <FirstName>. You will now have access to a cheaper rate on our wares, and some special equipment as well."
"Just agree to abide by guild rules and pay your annual dues, and you are in. What? Did you expect us to force you to run around doing quests for us? Gold is all we really care about here."
"Protect your fellow thieves when you can. Use as little force as possible when taking a target (we don't like assassins... if they are detected)."
"Finally, sell your goods here. You can use other shopkeepers, but you support your guild by dealing with me. I will also protect your identity from the guards, which others might not."
"I have a 'friend' who has gotten on the bad side of Enivid and languishes in prison at this very minute. If you could possibly get him free, you would be welcome here."
"You might have to sneak in and break him out of prison, but if you can convince Enivid to release him, that would be all for the better."
"If that is what it takes, then yes. But if you can convince Enivid to release him, that would be all for the better."
"All you need to do is open his door and let him out, or get release papers from Enivid and take them to the guard. Either way, once he is free return here."
"Then I don't think you will be a member of our thieves guild."
"You don't sound terribly convinced you can do this. Try not to get Stiletto, the prisoner, killed."
"There are several benefits to belonging to the thieves guild, but we will discuss those once you are a member. So will you rescue my friend?"
"Good. Try not to get Stiletto, the prisoner, killed. May Veragok cover you with his divine darkness and obscure you from your enemies."
"Now, was there anything else I can do for you?"
"Since you have joined our guild, we will, naturally, support your claim to the throne. Is there anything else I can do for you?"
"Your act of freeing Stiletto, no matter the reason, shows me you are a worthy candidate. I will vote for you on one condition."
"I have a 'friend' who got on the bad side of Enivid and languished in prison until someone set him free. I think that someone was you."
"He left a little gift here for you. He said he wished he could thank you in person, but he had some unfinished business to take care of."
"Your act of freeing a thief, no matter the reason, shows me you are a worthy candidate. I will vote for you on one condition."
"Simple, you must promise to stop crime in our city by supporting the thieves guild."
"I can sense the power of this cloak. It is a rare and valuable gift, <FirstName>."
He looks shocked, and then laughs. "I don't work that way, I'm afraid. Besides, it would look bad if one of the candidates suddenly died. It would probably cause something similar to a civil war."
"I have no respect for the man myself. He is haughty and irritable, but at least he leaves us thieves alone. I'll vote for him over Enivid any day."
"I guess I shall vote for Sir Becket. What choice do I have? This city doesn't need a ruler like Enivid who will try to 'purge' the streets of crime."
"We will be voting for you, past favors having been rendered. Anything else?"
"Sounds like a justification for breaking the law to me."
"This man makes sense, Trip can see that. Do you think if we ate his brain we would gain his knowledge?"
"What?"
"Oh, nothing, nothing. Trip never said a word, not one!"
"Oh yes, everything here is honestly purchased merchandise. No stolen goods are sold in this pawnshop. Not a chance."

"Well... there are occasional infractions... I suppose. One can never be truly positive. But if I recognize a particular item, I always offer to sell it back to the original owner for the cost I paid."
"That would be true if I was telling the thieves what to take, or who to take it from, but I don't. And if I happen to make a little profit occasionally, so does the local government."
"Taxation is the most profitable crime of all. Anything else, while you're throwing around insults?"
"I could... and occasionally I do, if I have a good buyer or don't like the person the item was stolen from... but that is a rarity. Usually I prefer to keep a fairly decent reputation."
"It is part of the deal we had with the late Banner. He allowed us full guild status, so long as I kept a tight rein on the thieves."
"The balance works well and keeps me in business with little interference from the guards."
"Very well. What would you like to talk about? Me, I like to talk about selling things. Maybe you would like to talk about buying some of those same things I like to sell."
"If it is precious to them, they pay. If not, they let me keep it and sell it, and I split the profits with them. It is better than the alternative, which is simply losing everything."
"Not at first, of course, but once they realize the alternative, they usually get over it. I have even had some thank me later. But that's rare. My policy just makes for better neighbors."
"Of course, if Enivid becomes the new lord, things could get more difficult, but I'm going to do everything in my power to make sure she doesn't get elected."
"I think she is beautiful, determined, and loves her community, but she is also cold-hearted and conceited. Others disagree with me, but that is how I see it. She must not win the next election."
"Stiletto mentioned you'd be by and said to treat you well. He left a little gift here for you and said he wished he could thank you in person, but he had some unfinished business to take care of."
"I can sense the power of this cloak. It is a rare and valuable gift, <FirstName>."
"Not yet."
"No, he is dead."
"Yes, I helped him escape."
"Yes, Enivid let him go."
"Goodbye."
"I would like to make a purchase."
